		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			Someone here previously mentioned a defensive healin proc. I think this is probably the best <br>way to go about fixing the shaman/slow related healing gap I also think its more in line with<br>the shaman as being a heavy buffing related class. The buff could act like a HoT essentially <br>by healing a specific percentage of incoming damage or just completely mitigate that percentage <br>of the dmg. This would help take the edge off healing and the amount healed/mitigated would be<br>directly related to how fast the mob is hitting you and how much damage it did this would make<br>it very very compatible with slowing a mob without directly increasing shaman heals to much <br>although I still beleive they need a small improvment in direct heals with this. To add on to<br>the Defensive healing/mitigation proc this is something that should also be of a short duration (1-5min) <br>and be dumped in the short buff box to avoid any major stacking and / or spell slot issues. <br><br>So far out of what I've read and thought about as my life as a shaman in EQ I have to say<br>this idea is by far the greatest and seems to be in-line with shaman more.<br><br>Quick version: <br><br>   1. Defensive Buff that heals a small percentage based on incoming damage ( or Mitigates completely)<br>      (majorly melee dmg realated and smaller portion for spell related dmg)<br><br>   2. This works because its directly related to how fast and how hard the mob is healing <br>      (making this compatible with slow)<br><br><br>   3. Make this a short buff. Keeping it in short buff box for avoiding stacking/spell slot issues.<br><br>On another note this needs to be an entire line of buffs covering from low to high levs.	
		</td></tr>
