	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=35560'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#CC6600;font-weight:bold; '>Warren_Magnuson</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Master<br>
			
				Posts: 120<br>
				
				Registered: 05-19-2004
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=35560'>







</a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=shamanbalance&message.id=5256#M5256">43</a> of 109
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 404 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			The big idea that many seem to be drawn to is the idea of stances for shaman like the druid.  I fear the biggest problem with that analogy is that Druid stances are being based off their Offensive role and their Healing role.  What people are proposing with the shaman is a stance that would increase slowing power or increase healing power but the problem is, these are functions of the same thing... combined, a shaman is up to the task of being able to main heal which is the entire point of the re-invisioning process.<br><br>Whether you like to main heal or not.... SOE believes that the shaman should be able to main heal (and from an original design standpoint, rightly so).  Shaman main heal effectively because of a combination of our healing/slowing abilities.  Stances that would hamper our abilities to do one or the other is counter to this role.  Plus one thing people have not mentioned and people should realize, not all monsters in the same area slow at the same level.   What happens when you come across a mob that is very slowable and then in the next pull, another monster that is only slightly slowable?   Worse, what happens if both come at the same time?  And finally, in the fast paced environment of efficient adventuring (exp'ing) when monsters are coming one right after the other, how often do you expect to be able to toggle your stances?   And it's not as if monsters come with signs over their head "Hi!  I"m Herb.  You can partially slow me."   "Hello, I'm the Brothers Kringle, you can't slow me at all."<br><br>On the basis of the class reinvisioning post, it appears obvious that Shaman are going to be defined as a Priest class so therefore a candidate to main heal in a group.  Clerics, who used to be up in arms about the idea of other main healing classes, are going to be given soloing capabilities to compensate since their main argument used to be that the only way they could get exp was by grouping and if SOE allowed other main healer classes, clerics would become undesirable... Well now no one gets to have it both ways anymore.  Equal solo-ability means equal sitting on the bench.  <br><br>So before I digress too far off topic, the discussion needs to orient itself on how to make a Shaman an effective main healer as long as slowing is part of the mechanics.  A proc is an interesting idea but SOE will not relegate healing to a passive role.   Except for HOT's which as people have pointed out in the past, does not save a player from death like a burst heal will, healing will and must remain an Active role.<br><br>We have to explore the bounds of what is possible and what is not, design and coding-wise.  For instance, is it even possible to code into shaman healing, a percentage healing increase, on a single target being attacked, based off the percentage the attacking monster has been slowed by.  Sounds like a lot of detail to be kept track of and a coding nightmare to me, but if there are any coders out there, how feasible is that?<br><br>If that is not possible, what can be done to do something similar and compensate?<br><br><br>Enough of my musings for now,<br>Best Regards to All,<br>Warren Magnuson	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
